{"summary":"All four amendments are technically sound. Three identify concrete correctness and recoverability bugs in retry or legacy-repair paths, and the duplication amendment addresses subtle shared normalization logic that should not be maintained in two separate implementations.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-4-54b5dd71","decision":"accept","rationale":"`MilestoneSnapshot.updated_at` is defined as the time the snapshot was last written, but replaying a completion currently reuses the stored terminal timestamp from lineage. That can make `updated_at` move backward, or remain stale, relative to intervening or current snapshot writes. The journal/event timestamp can stay anchored to the original completion, but the snapshot timestamp should be monotonic."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-65a16a24","decision":"accept","rationale":"The service and filesystem adapter both implement the same legacy attempt-collapse and merge rules with only superficial differences. That logic is subtle and affects both snapshot reconciliation and per-bead lineage queries, so keeping two copies creates a real risk of silent behavioral drift. Centralizing it improves maintainability and robustness."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-0195eaea","decision":"accept","rationale":"The no-`run_id` path in `FsTaskRunLineageStore::update_task_run()` rejects the exact legacy two-row shape of one attempt recorded as `running` plus terminal, because it filters out the superseded start row and then requires a single open match. That makes replaying a historical completion fail with an ambiguity error instead of repairing snapshot/journal state, which breaks the backward-compatible retry/repair contract."},{"amendment_id":"fr-4-013c9cb2","decision":"accept","rationale":"`record_bead_start()` appends lineage before snapshot and journal writes and does not deduplicate repeated starts for the same `(bead_id, project_id, run_id)`. If a partial failure triggers a retry, the file can contain duplicate running rows for the same run, and later finalization fails because `update_task_run()` sees multiple exact `run_id` matches and treats them as ambiguous. That is a concrete idempotency and recoverability defect."}]}